==History==

It was known among locals as the "secret waterfall". Now known as Pego do Inferno (Hell's Pool/Pit of hell) due to a popular local legend about the site about a carriage that fell into the lake and was never found. It was said that anyone who fell into it would go straight to hell.<ref>
{{cite web
 | url = http://www.theportugalnews.com/news/view/1164-26
 | title = Tavira to transform Pego do Inferno into living museum
 | accessdate = 2014-05-02}}
</ref>

The legend also says that the bodies of the occupants of the cart and the animals were never found and that divers were not able to find the bottom of the lake, which has been called (Hell's Pool/Pit of hell) ever since.

Barriers and bins, were installed in 2000, as well as a small cafe.<ref>
{{cite web
 | url = http://www.theportugalnews.com/news/vandalism-forces-closure-of-natural-beauty-spot/6804
 | title = Vandalism forces closure of natural beauty spot
 | accessdate = 2014-05-02}}
</ref> 

A fire closed the area in 2012. Since then, the municipality of Tavira has not reopened the space to the public and the facilities have been abandoned. However, every summer vacationers and locals still visit the small waterfall<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://contramapa.com/2017/09/18/pego-do-inferno/|title=Pego do Inferno: A Cascata de Tavira|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref>.

